# 🔐 Cloud-Native Secrets Management with CyberArk Conjur, Terraform & AWS

![Terraform](https://img.shields.io/badge/Terraform-1.x-623CE4?logo=terraform)
![AWS](https://img.shields.io/badge/AWS-EC2-FF9900?logo=amazonaws)
![CyberArk](https://img.shields.io/badge/CyberArk-Conjur-blue)
![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/Python-3.x-3776AB?logo=python)
![Docker](https://img.shields.io/badge/Docker-Compose-2496ED?logo=docker)
![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-green)

A production-inspired secrets management solution demonstrating how applications can securely retrieve credentials at runtime using **CyberArk Conjur OSS**, **Terraform**, **AWS**, **Docker**, and **Python**, eliminating hardcoded secrets and implementing a least-privilege authentication model.

---

# 📖 Overview

Applications frequently store database passwords, API keys, and service credentials inside source code, configuration files, or environment variables. This creates several security and operational challenges:

- Secrets can be accidentally committed to source control.
- Password rotation requires application changes.
- Applications often receive excessive permissions.
- Secret management becomes decentralized and difficult to audit.

This project demonstrates a centralized approach using **CyberArk Conjur OSS**.

Infrastructure is provisioned using **Terraform**, while a Python application authenticates to Conjur using a dedicated **least-privilege Host Identity** and retrieves secrets securely through the **Conjur REST API**.

---

