## 🏗️ Architecture

```mermaid
flowchart LR

    subgraph AWS["AWS Infrastructure (Terraform)"]
        TF["Terraform"]
        EC2["EC2 Instance"]
        IAM["IAM Role"]
        VPC["VPC & Security Groups"]

        TF --> VPC
        TF --> IAM
        TF --> EC2
    end

    subgraph APP["Application"]
        PY["Python Client"]
    end

    subgraph CONJUR["CyberArk Conjur OSS"]
        AUTH["Host Authentication"]
        POLICY["Authorization Policies"]
        SECRET["Secrets Store"]
    end

    EC2 --> PY

    PY -->|1. Authenticate using Host Identity| AUTH
    AUTH -->|2. Access Token| PY

    PY -->|3. Request Database Credentials| SECRET
    POLICY --> SECRET

    SECRET -->|4. Username & Password| PY

    PY -->|Uses Credentials Securely| DB[(Database)]
```

### Architecture Overview

1. **Terraform** provisions the AWS infrastructure, including networking, IAM resources, and an EC2 instance.

2. The **Python application** runs on the EC2 instance and authenticates to **CyberArk Conjur** using a dedicated Host Identity.

3. Upon successful authentication, Conjur issues a short-lived access token.

4. The application requests the required database credentials from Conjur.

5. Conjur evaluates authorization policies and returns only the secrets the application is permitted to access.

6. The application uses the retrieved credentials at runtime without storing them in source code or configuration files.


## 🔄 Authentication Flow

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram

    participant App as Python Application
    participant Conjur as CyberArk Conjur

    App->>Conjur: Authenticate (Host Identity + API Key)
    Conjur-->>App: Access Token

    App->>Conjur: Request Database Username
    Conjur-->>App: Username

    App->>Conjur: Request Database Password
    Conjur-->>App: Password

    App->>App: Connect using retrieved credentials
```


